PUH-BrianMartell CUP (“Cost per New Fact”) projections for 2030–2050 are sobering — the trend of exponential growth in cost with diminishing novel discoveries continues unless a paradigm shift occurs. Current baseline (1995–2025): ~$140B cumulative, ~6 novel facts → average CUP ≈ $23B/fact, recent LHC era ~$45B/fact. Projections assuming no major breakthrough (business-as-usual: larger colliders, precision hunts): •  2030: Next-gen facilities (FCC, muon collider studies) ~$30–50B → 0–1 new fact → CUP ~$60–100B/fact. •  2040: Mega-colliders or space-based ~$100B+ → likely null results → CUP ~$150–300B/fact. •  2050: Hypothetical Planck-scale probes ~$500B+ → CUP potentially trillions per fact if no new physics. Exponential fit: CUP_n ≈ 12 × e^{0.15(n-1995)} billion USD (rough from historical). By 2050, CUP could exceed $500B per new fact — unsustainable, forcing crisis or pivot.
